Looking at the mutation, the change is in the regex pattern used to prepend `http://` to URLs:

- Original: `/^(?!(?:\w+:)?\/\/)/` - matches `\w+:` (one or more word characters followed by colon)
- Mutated: `/^(?!(?:\w:)?\/\/)/` - matches `\w:` (exactly one word character followed by colon)

This affects the case where a URL has a protocol like `http://` or `https://`. The original regex correctly handles protocols with multiple characters (like `http:`, `https:`), while the mutated version only handles single-character protocols.

The key scenario: when `parse` is called with a URL that has no base URL and no protocol prefix, and the URL doesn't match `^\.*\/|^(?!localhost)\w+:`, the code tries to add `http://`. 

Wait, let me re-read. The mutation is in the `else` branch when there's no `baseUrlStr`. The condition `!/^\.*\/|^(?!localhost)\w+:/.test(currentUrlStr)` - if this is false (URL starts with `./`, `/`, or has a protocol), we skip the replacement. If true, we do the replacement.

For a URL like `example.com/path` (no protocol, no leading slash), the condition is true, so we enter the block and prepend `http://`.

The difference: with original regex `/^(?!(?:\w+:)?\/\/)/`, it won't prepend `http://` if the URL already starts with `http://` (multi-char protocol). With mutated regex `/^(?!(?:\w:)?\/\/)/`, it won't prepend if URL starts with single-char protocol followed by `://`.

So for a URL like `http://example.com`, the original wouldn't prepend (because `http:` matches `\w+:`), but the mutated version would prepend (because `http:` doesn't match `\w:` - it's more than one char).

But wait - `http://example.com` would be caught by `^(?!localhost)\w+:` in the condition check, so it wouldn't enter the block at all.

Let me think about `example.com` - no protocol. The condition `!/^\.*\/|^(?!localhost)\w+:/.test('example.com')` is true, so we enter the block. The original regex prepends `http://` to get `http://example.com`. The mutated regex also prepends `http://`. Same result.

What about a URL like `ab://example.com`? The condition check: `^(?!localhost)\w+:` matches `ab:`, so condition is false, we skip the block. Same for both.

The difference would be with a single-character protocol like `a://example.com` vs multi-char. But more practically, the regex inside the block: for `example.com`, both prepend `http://`. The difference only matters if somehow a URL enters the block that already has a protocol.

Actually, looking more carefully - the lookahead in the replacement regex: original `(?!\w+:\/\/)` prevents replacing if already has protocol. Mutated `(?!\w:\/\/)` only prevents if single-char protocol. So `http://example.com` entering the block would get `http://` prepended again by mutated version.

